value.0: The grotesquely distorted figure before you seems to exist in a constant state of pain. A gray, patternless mange sprouts from once-pink skin and the creature's eyes have a fevered look about them.

"<Lord/Lady> <LastName>, is it really you?" The creature struggles with the words, lisping against its unnaturally large teeth. "You've changed so much since last I saw you but I still recognize your voice."
"I've followed you all the way from the King's court," simpers the creature. "I had hoped you would still recognize me within this flesh. It's me, m'<Lord/Lady>: Baron Androleth. Don't you remember?"
The fevered chattering of the creature's teeth intensifies. "I was not always brought so low, m'<Lord/Lady>. It is a warlock's curse that I suffer for my loyalty."

The shrewish face gives way to a ghastly smile. The creature's ragged lips are cut and raw from its own teeth. "So something of my former self survives this warlock's curse? It is for my loyalty that I suffer so."
The creature's teeth chatter with fever. "But I've come all this way, m'<Lord/Lady>! I've suffered much for my loyalty, even this dreadful warlock's curse. I was not always like this."
The creature falls, groveling, to the floor, the whining, lisping drone of its voice continuing unabated. "Only to you, <Lord/Lady> <LastName>. Only and always to you. It's why they cursed me."
"But I would change nothing if it meant changing that, m'<Lord/Lady>." The creature groveling before you shudders with a sudden chill and its teeth resumed their fevered chattering.
The creature shakes its horrid head. "No, m'<Lord/Lady>. I have already travelled far to see your face again. I am sick and weary and would only slow you down."
"You do what you must do and I will rest here to regain my strength." The wretched creature turns from you, seeking a perch that might be free of rats.
The creature bobs its horrid head. "Yes, m'<Lord/Lady>. Sometimes loyalty requires disobedience but I will do my best to protect you from afar. I will stay here to regain my strength."

The creature seems surprised by your response, cringing back suspiciously. "But loyalty is all we have in this life. It is worth more than a hall of gold! Even if you spurn my loyalty, m'<Lord/Lady>, it is yours."
The creature claws at its chest in distress. "No, they're not mine, I swear on it! They hate me even more than they do you, but they're drawn to me."
"They're a part of the curse, following me everywhere I go, gnawing on my tail, clawing at my feet... Please, m'<Lord/Lady>, you must believe me."
"What reason did I have to stay, m'<Lord/Lady>? My family persuaded of my treachery, my home and barony in the hands of my own enemies, my body cursed beyond recognition... All for my loyalty."

"Yes, to sleep each night upon wet stone, burrowing in dung for warmth and detritus for safety... To travel through every city sewer between here and home, your nose made more sensitive to its stench."

"To find oneself ridden by fleas, reviled by man and beast alike. To feel your very bones stretch and twist beneath your ravaged skin. All of it made more cruel by the memory that I was once like you."
The creature peers through the mists of Brogan's Tears, seeking a resting place where it can be free of the rats that endlessly pursue it.
Leave the pitiful creature.
"You be okay?"
"Are you alright?"
"What sort of beast you be?"
"What manner of beast are you?"
"Move an inch and me crush you, beast!"
"Stand back, beast, or face your death!"
"You stay back."
"Stay away from me."
"Why you come here?"
"What brings you to this place?"
"How you know my name?"
"How do you know my name?"
"Ha! You be baron in some king's court?"
"Liar! You, a baron in a king's court?"
"Uh, Baron Androleth... Yuh, of course."
"Ah, Baron Androleth... Of course."
"Sorry, me not know anyone by that name."
"Sorry, I don't know anyone by that name."
"What you be so loyal to?"
"What is it that you are so loyal to?"
"Okay, you come with me. Me take care of you."
"Look, come with me. I'll take care of you."
"If you be so loyal, then go away."
"If you're so loyal, then stay out of my sight."
"Don't you be loyal to me, okay?"
"Well, don't be loyal to me, all right?"
"Then make rats play nice."
"Then call off your rats."
"Why you come so far?"
"Why have you come so far?"
"It be warlock curse, huh?"
"A warlock's curse, is it?"
